==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*wunda-'', from Indo-European ''*wan-, *awa(n)-''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[wunda]] ''n'' (Dutch [[wond]]), Old High German [[wund]] ''adj'', [[wunta]] ''n'' (German [[wund#German|wund]], [[Wunde]]), Old Norse [[und]] ''n'' (Danish [[vann]]), Gothic [[𐍅𐌿𐌽𐌳𐍃]] ''adj''.  The IE root is also the source of Welsh [[ym-wan]] ‘fight’, Baltic ''*vati-'' (Lithuanian [[votis|vòtis]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /wʊnd/

===Adjective===
'''wund'''
# [[wounded]], [[injured]], [[sore]]

===Noun===
'''wund''' ''f''
# a [[wound]], an [[injury]]

